Observation:

  1. Mostly complete dataset Many columns have 0 missing values.
  2. Children: Only 4 missing entries negligible, can drop or impute.
  3. Country: 488 missing very small compared to 119k rows.
  4. Agent: 16,340 missing (~14%) may represent direct bookings.
  5. Company: 112,593 missing (~94%) most guests do not book via company contracts.
  6. Other columns (e.g., hotel, lead_time, adr, reservation_status) are fully complete.

Fill missing values using suitable methods such as: Mean or median (for numerical values) Mode or placeholder (for categorical values)

In[4]:
df['children'] = df['children'].fillna(df['children'].median())
df['country'] = df['country'].fillna(df['country'].mode()[0])
df['agent'] = df['agent'].fillna('Unknown')
df['company'] = df['company'].fillna('Unknown')

print(df.isnull().sum())

4. Converting Data types

In[11]:
# Convert date column
df["reservation_status_date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["reservation_status_date"], errors="coerce")

# Numeric columns
numeric_cols = [
    "lead_time", "adr", "stays_in_week_nights", "stays_in_weekend_nights",
    "adults", "children", "babies", "previous_cancellations",
    "previous_bookings_not_canceled", "required_car_parking_spaces",
    "total_of_special_requests"
]

for col in numeric_cols:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors="coerce")

# Categorical columns
categorical_cols = [
    "hotel", "meal", "country", "market_segment", "distribution_channel",
    "reserved_room_type", "assigned_room_type", "deposit_type",
    "customer_type", "reservation_status"
]

for col in categorical_cols:
    df[col] = df[col].astype("category")

Observation:

  • The dataset contains 119,390 entries and 36 columns.
  • Date column (reservation_status_date) is now in datetime format, enabling time-series analysis.
  • Numerical columns (lead_time, adr, stays_in_week_nights, adults, children, etc.) are properly stored as int64/float64 for computations.
  • Categorical columns (hotel, meal, country, market_segment, distribution_channel, deposit_type, etc.) are stored as category type, which optimizes memory usage and speeds up grouping/aggregation.
  • The dataset is now clean, memory-efficient, and analysis-ready.

Univariate analysis

One Numerical column-total_of_special_requests

In[20]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

sns.set_style("whitegrid")

fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(15,10))
plt.suptitle("Univariate Analysis - Total of Special Requests", fontsize=18, color="darkred", weight="bold")

# Histogram
sns.histplot(data=df, x="total_of_special_requests", bins=10, color="#4682B4", ax=axs[0,0])
axs[0,0].set_title("Histogram", fontsize=14, weight="bold")

# Box plot
sns.boxplot(data=df, x="total_of_special_requests", color="#32CD32", ax=axs[0,1])
axs[0,1].set_title("Box Plot", fontsize=14, weight="bold")

# Violin plot
sns.violinplot(data=df, x="total_of_special_requests", color="#FF8C00", ax=axs[1,0])
axs[1,0].set_title("Violin Plot", fontsize=14, weight="bold")

# KDE plot
sns.kdeplot(data=df, x="total_of_special_requests", fill=True, color="#800080", ax=axs[1,1])
axs[1,1].set_title("KDE Plot", fontsize=14, weight="bold")

plt.savefig("C:\Datasets\one_numerical_univariate.png")
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96])
plt.show();

One Categorial

In[21]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18,6))
plt.suptitle("Univariate Analysis - Categorical Variable (Hotel Type)", fontsize=18, color="darkred", weight="bold")

# Bright color palette
bright_colors = sns.color_palette("Set1")

# 1. Bar Plot
df['hotel'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', ax=axs[0], color=bright_colors)
axs[0].set_title("Bar Plot - Hotel Type", fontsize=14, weight="bold")
axs[0].set_ylabel("Count")

# 2. Pie Chart
axs[1].pie(
    df['hotel'].value_counts(),
    labels=df['hotel'].value_counts().index,
    autopct="%.1f%%",
    colors=bright_colors,
    startangle=90,
    wedgeprops={"edgecolor":"white"}
)
axs[1].set_title("Pie Chart - Hotel Type", fontsize=14, weight="bold")

# 3. Count Plot
sns.countplot(data=df, x="hotel", palette="Set1", ax=axs[2])
axs[2].set_title("Count Plot - Hotel Type", fontsize=14, weight="bold")

plt.savefig("C:\Datasets\one_categorical_univariate.png")
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0,0,1,0.95])
plt.show();

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Create figure first
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))

# Regression plot
sns.regplot(
    data=df,
    x='previous_cancellations',
    y='booking_changes',
    color='purple',
    scatter_kws={'alpha':0.6, 'edgecolor':'w'}
)

# Title and labels with font styling
plt.title("Regression Plot: Previous Cancellations vs Booking Changes", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', fontname='Arial')
plt.xlabel("Previous Cancellations", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', fontname='Arial')
plt.ylabel("Booking Changes", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', fontname='Arial')

# Grid lines
plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.6)

# Save figure
plt.savefig(r"C:\Datasets\Regression_plot.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")

# Show plot
plt.show()

In[39]:
cross_tab = pd.crosstab(
    [df['deposit_type'], df['customer_type']], 
    df['reservation_status'], 
    normalize='index'
)

cross_tab.plot(
    kind="bar", 
    stacked=True, 
    figsize=(12,6), 
    colormap="Set2"
)

plt.title("Stacked Bar: Deposit Type & Customer Type vs Reservation Status", fontsize=15, fontweight="bold")
plt.ylabel("Proportion", fontsize=12)
plt.xlabel("Deposit Type & Customer Type", fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend(title="Reservation Status", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("C:\Datasets\Stacked_bar_multivariate.png")
plt.show();
